Welcome to the AWS Snowball Edge Primer course! The AWS Snowball Edge Primer consists of three courses or modules to help familiarize you with the AWS Snowball Edge service offering.

Course Title: Configure and Deploy AWS Client VPN
Description: AWS Client VPN provides access to AWS resources in an on-premises network from any location.  With global requirements for work from home, connecting and staying connected is important.  This course contains two independent lessons:

Course Title: Moving To Managed Databases on AWS
Description: The lift-and-shift strategy is a common move for organizations making their first foray into the cloud. This lift-and-shift strategy may feel like the easiest way to move to the cloud. Your architecture map still looks similar, and your team’s responsibilities don’t change. But you're not getting the full benefits of the cloud.

Course Title: Cloud Audit Academy FDW Interactive Modules
Description: In this course, you will learn how Amazon Web Services (AWS) offerings can be used to assist with U.S. federal and U.S. Department of Defense (DoD) security and compliance requirements. This course supplements the Cloud Audit Academy (CAA) for Federal and Department of Defense (DoD) Workloads (FDW) in AWS instructor-led training (ILT).Each module includes interactive walkthroughs of the AWS Management Console, AWS services relevant to each of the modules, or NIST control families covered in the course. The walkthroughs are an optional exercise at the discretion of the instructor.

This course introduces you to the best practices and tools that help you optimize and improve the performance of your Amazon DocumentDB (with MongoDB compatibility) clusters. You will learn how to design your Amazon DocumentDB database for optimized performance by monitoring key metrics and troubleshooting the most common challenges. Following performance-tuning best practices can help save costs related to performance and billing.

Course Title: Architecting on AWS - Accelerator - Online Course Supplement
Description: We have updated this course on October 18, 2022, to correct a problem that was impacting course completion. If you are enrolled in the course and have not completed it, your progress may be impacted. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause.

Course Title: AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Amazon FSx File Gateway
Description: Welcome to the AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Amazon FSx File Gateway course! Amazon FSx File Gateway optimizes on-premises access to fully managed, highly reliable file shares in Amazon FSx for Windows File Server.

Course Title: AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Tape Gateway
Description: Welcome to the AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Tape Gateway course! Tape Gateway replaces using physical tapes on premises with virtual tapes in AWS without you needing to change your existing backup workflows.

Course Title: AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Amazon S3 File Gateway
Description: Welcome to the AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Amazon S3 File Gateway course! In this course, you learn how to connect your on-premises file, database, and backup applications to cloud storage using Amazon S3 File Gateway. You examine how to plan, secure, manage, monitor, and optimize Amazon S3 File Gateway deployments.

Course Title: AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Volume Gateway
Description: Welcome to the AWS Storage Gateway Deep Dive: Volume Gateway course! Volume Gateway presents cloud-backed Internet Small Computer System Interface (iSCSI) block storage volumes to your applications to provide seamless integration between your IT environment and the Amazon Web Services (AWS) storage infrastructure for your data protection, recovery, and migration needs.

Course Title: Securing Data in Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS)
Description: Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) provides a simple, serverless, set-and-forget elastic file system for use with AWS Cloud services and on-premises resources. It is built to scale on demand to petabytes without disrupting applications, growing and shrinking automatically as you add and remove files, eliminating the need to provision and manage capacity to accommodate growth.

Course Title: Designing and Deploying an Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) Solution
Description: Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) provides a simple, serverless, set-and-forget elastic file system for use with AWS Cloud services and on-premises resources. It is built to scale on demand to petabytes without disrupting applications, growing and shrinking automatically as you add and remove files, eliminating the need to provision and manage capacity to accommodate growth.

Course Title: Managing, Monitoring, and Optimizing your Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) Solution
Description: Amazon Elastic File System (Amazon EFS) provides a simple, serverless, set-and-forget elastic file system for use with AWS Cloud services and on-premises resources. It is built to scale on demand to petabytes without disrupting applications, growing and shrinking automatically as you add and remove files, eliminating the need to provision and manage capacity to accommodate growth.

Course Title: Troubleshooting: Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS)
Description: In this course, you will learn how to view important information about troubleshooting Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS). You can use this information to help troubleshoot common issues and provide effective support case details if you need to escalate to Amazon Web Services (AWS) Support.

Course Title: Design Patterns for AWS Step Functions
Description: AWS Step Functions is a low-code visual workflow service used to orchestrate Amazon Web Services (AWS) services, automate business processes, and build serverless applications. In this course, you learn how to implement design patterns in your Step Functions state machines and why to use each one. You also learn best practices to use while implementing these design patterns.

Course Title: Managing Applications at Scale with Amazon ECS
Observing, Troubleshooting, and Optimizing Workloads Running on Amazon ECS
Description: In this course you learn how to gain observability to your applications running on Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS). You learn how to collect metrics, logs, and traces at the system and application level. You also learn how to apply the information you gather to identify and correct problems.

Course Title: Deep Dive: Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) Cost Optimization
Description: Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) is an easy-to-use, high-performance, block storage service designed for use with Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) for both throughput-intensive and transaction-intensive workloads at any scale. You can deploy a broad range of workloads on Amazon EBS, such as relational and non-relational databases, enterprise applications, containerized applications, big data analytics engines, file systems, and media workflows. In this course, you learn about cost optimization for your Amazon EBS deployments. You learn to apply the principles of the Cost Optimization pillar of the AWS Well-Architected Framework to your Amazon EBS volumes, identify common cost optimization opportunities, apply pricing and performance consideration to choosing Amazon EBS volume types, and use AWS Cost Optimizer to help manage your cost optimization opportunities.

Course Title: Deep Dive: Managing and Monitoring Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS)
Description: Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) supports a wide range of both transaction-intensive and throughput-intensive workloads on Amazon Web Services (AWS). In this fourth course of the Amazon EBS deep dive, you learn how to manage your EBS volumes, how to back up and restore volumes, and best practices for working with volumes. The course introduces you to how Amazon uses AWS Key Management Service (AWS KMS) to encrypt and decrypt your volumes and snapshots, and how to restore volumes using different encryptions keys. Finally, this course explains the value of monitoring and auditing Amazon EBS using tools such as Amazon CloudWatch and AWS CloudTrail.

Course Title: Deep Dive: Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS) Performance Optimization
Description: We have updated this course on September 20th, 2022 to correct a problem that was impacting course completion. If you are enrolled in the course and have not completed it, your progress may be impacted. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause

Course Title: Deep Dive: Architecting with Amazon Elastic Block Store (Amazon EBS)
Managing the Application Lifecycle in Amazon ECS
Description: In this course, you learn how to manage applications at scale on Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS). You learn how to select the best method for building an Amazon ECS environment, how to select the best deployment options for your application, and how to manage your application pipelines throughout your applications’ lifecycle.

Course Title: Building Enterprise Architectures in Amazon ECS
Description: In this course, you learn how to make infrastructure choices to support containerized applications running on Amazon Elastic Container Service (Amazon ECS) at an enterprise scale. You learn how to scope requirements based on your application, select the best architecture to support your application, and design reusable infrastructure patterns that are secure, performant, and resilient.

Course Title: Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery
Advanced Testing Practices Using AWS DevOps Tools
Deep Dive into AWS IoT Authentication and Authorization
Description: Security is a central concern for all of Amazon Web Services (AWS). Security is extremely important in the field of IoT (Internet of Things) because IoT devices are physically accessible. Authentication and authorization are the foundations of a secure IoT infrastructure.This course explores the concepts of IoT authentication and authorization within AWS IoT. You will learn about the IoT control plane and data plane and how to authenticate and authorize to both. This course is intended for students who would like to securely connect devices, mobile apps, desktop apps, web apps, or the CLI to AWS IoT. You will learn about using different authentication methods and their appropriate authorization policies.

Course Title: Deep Dive on Amazon Rekognition: Building Computer Visions Based Smart Applications
Modernize .NET Applications – Infrastructure as Code and CI/CD
Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) Cost Optimization
Description: With Amazon S3, you can lower costs without sacrificing performance. Amazon S3 lets you take control of costs and continuously optimize your spending. In this course, you learn about the techniques you can use to optimize your Amazon S3 costs. You also explore the tools available to understand the costs associated with Amazon S3 and forecast future billing.

Course Title: Securing and Protecting Your Data in Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3)
Description: With Amazon S3, you can use a number of different approaches when addressing data protection, including preventing buckets from being publicly accessible, implementing access controls, and encrypting data at rest and in transit. Amazon S3 makes it easy to protect your data from security incidents. In this course, you learn Amazon S3 security best practices to help improve your security posture and methods to prevent unwanted access to your data or comply with business and regulatory obligations.

Course Title: Build a Text Classification Model with AWS Glue and Amazon SageMaker
Building in Amazon Honeycode: App Design with Data in Mind
Description: In this course, you will learn how to successfully build an app from your initial idea. The course begins with a lesson on key data modeling concepts in Amazon Honeycode. It then guides you through an exercise to explore how data operates throughout an app using a Honeycode template app.You will practice identifying an app's data model just by navigating the live app. You will also learn how to connect table data to an app, including common features and patterns to help manage data throughout the app. Finally, you will examine the data model of an app in Honeycode Tables.

There are many ways you can optimize your implementation to reduce administrative overhead, efficiently scale to meet organizational demand, reduce costs, and increase reliability through troubleshooting and well-architected design. This curriculum focuses on the knowledge and skills IT administrators need to provide their users with fast, responsive desktops while keeping administrative overhead at bay.

Course Title: Managing Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3)
Description: Amazon S3 provides a full portfolio of storage management tools that help you easily manage your storage as it grows. With Amazon S3, you can organize, automate, and monitor your data to meet your specific business and organizational requirements.

Course Title: Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) Performance Optimization
Description: As your organization and business grow, more users, applications, and other AWS services interact with your objects residing in Amazon S3. Optimizing performance of such interactions can help you minimize downtime, increase efficiency, and improve customer experience.

Course Title: Section Four: Amazon S3 Storage Management
Description: In this module, you will manage your storage by exploring bucket options, versioning, lifecycle policies, object tags, inventory, cross-region replication, and automation with triggers.

Course Title: Advanced Architecting on AWS - Online Course Supplement
Description:

This Online Course Supplement (OCS) is a companion resource to the Advanced Architecting on AWS classroom training, which introduces students to topics that are important for advanced architect professionals to know. The OCS provides videos and resources for each course topic, and contains review questions and answers to help you review information from the course.

Course Title: Get Connected: Amazon Honeycode APIs and Integrations
Description: In this course, you will learn how to connect Amazon Honeycode to other applications and services. The course begins with an overview of two different approaches to connecting to Honeycode: integrations and Honeycode application programming interfaces (APIs). It guides you through examples of how to set up and implement integrated solutions in Honeycode using Amazon AppFlow and Zapier. Finally, the course provides a brief overview of Honeycode APIs. You will learn how to identify which Honeycode API meets your use case and how to set up an API request.

This course will help you understand how to enable chat in the routing profiles and contact flows of your Amazon Connect instance and through your customer web page. The course will step you through the process to deploy and test a chat demonstration with your Amazon Connect contact flows.

This course will help you understand the best practices recommended by AWS when you design, create, and support an Amazon Connect contact center. These best practices are aligned with the five pillars of the AWS Well-Architected framework.

Course Title: Building Better Bots Using Amazon Connect
Description: This course will show you how to enhance the caller experience in your Amazon Connect call center using a custom chatbot created using Amazon Lex. Amazon Lex is a service that enables you to build highly engaging user experiences and lifelike conversational interactions. You will be able to review the contact flow of your Amazon Lex chatbot and see how design changes impact the chat experience in real time.

In this course, you will be introduced to AWS Systems Manager and dive deep into real-world scenarios. Learn how Systems Manager management service helps you automatically collect software inventory, apply OS patches, and automate administration tasks and complex workflows. You will also see how to eliminate the need for bastion hosts to manage your resources. You will review capabilities including Run Command, State Manager, Inventory, Patch Manager, Maintenance Window, Automation, Parameter Store, Session Manager, OpsCenter, Explorer, Change Calendar, and Distributor.

Course Title: Deep Dive into AWS IoT Rules Engine
Description: This is an interactive course that includes two hours of topical information and two hours of hands-on exercises that are performed within the AWS Console. Through this course, you learn to utilize the AWS IoT rules engine to leverage incoming MQTT messages to interact with AWS services. This course was designed so that you can gain comprehensive and deep knowledge about the AWS IoT rules engine, or select individual topics to deepen your current understanding.

Course Title: Dive Deep into Amazon Connect Reporting and Metrics
Description: We have updated this course on December 2, 2022 to correct a problem that was impacting course completion. If you are enrolled in the course and have not completed it, your progress may be impacted. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause

Course Title: Amazon Connect: Build a Custom Call Control Panel
Description: This course will help you understand how Amazon Connect allows you to integrate a Custom Call Control Panel (CCP) into a Customer Relationship Management (CRM) environment. The course describes how to integrate using a standard deployment or by creating a custom-built user interface, by leveraging the Streams API provided by Amazon Connect.

This course will help you understand how to access Amazon CloudWatch and use CloudWatch Logs to create insights, metric filters, dashboards, and alarms to monitor and troubleshoot the performance of your Amazon Connect contact center.

Course Title: Using a Token-based Approach to Build Highly Secure, Stateless, and Decoupled Applications
Description: You say you want functionality beyond sessions, cookies, federation, and other traditional tools in your toolkit? Are you building highly secure, stateless, decoupled applications? In this session, you’ll learn how to use a tokens-based approach to transcend the critical limitations of traditional approaches. This step-by-step course will show you everything you need to know—so you can focus on your application logic and let AWS do the heavy lifting for you.

In this course, you will get an introduction to Lambda@Edge and understand its use cases, deep dive into how it works under the hood, learn how you can write functions and finally pick up some best practices from our experience with serverless customers.

Course Title: Hands-on Rekognition: Automated Image and Video Analysis
Description: Facial recognition and comparison is a challenge—determining mood or attitude from facial recognition data is a complex problem. In this overview of Amazon Rekognition, we’ll demonstrate how facial recognition works with streaming video and discuss facial recognition and facial comparison in detail, with code examples and a self-paced lab to help clarify key points. Along the way, we’ll introduce you to important concepts and explore working with still images, stored videos, and streaming video.

Course Title: Deep Dive into Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS)
Deep Dive into Concepts and Tools for Analyzing Streaming Data on AWS
Description: In this course, we will introduce basic stream processing concepts and discuss strategies that are commonly used to address the challenges that arise from querying of streaming data. We will discuss different time semantics, processing guarantees, and elaborate how to deal with reordering and late arriving of events. We will also address the benefits of managing state inside a stream processing engine and highlight how it changes the way we build architectures in a streaming domain.

You have successfully planned and ordered an AWS Snowcone. Once you receive Snowcone, you will configure the network settings, users, and (optionally) start the compute service in order to prepare to deploy.

Course Title: AWS Snowball Edge Logistics and Planning
Description: Welcome to the AWS Snowball Edge Logistics and Planning course! This course consists of two courses or modules to help you gain a deeper understanding the processes of how to implement the AWS Snowball Edge service offering.

Course Title: AWS Snowball Edge: Using Snowball Edge

In this course, you will learn how to create and use macros. The focus is on creating and using macros in AWS CloudFormation templates.

Course Title: Deep Dive with Security: AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM)
Description: We have updated this course on September 13, 2022 to correct a problem that was impacting course completion. If you are enrolled in the course and have not completed it, your progress may be impacted. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause.

Course Title: Deep Dive on AWS Fargate: Building Serverless Containers at Scale
Description: Containers allow you to craft sophisticated cloud-native applications, but how do you manage scale? In this course you will learn how to better launch and manage your large-scale containerized workloads with AWS Fargate. Dmitriy Novikov will walk through the essentials of AWS Fargate to get the most out of your container deployment and management strategy.

Course Title: Best Practices for Data Warehousing with Amazon Redshift
Description: In this course, you will learn about the concepts of implementing a data warehouse using Amazon Redshift. You will learn about basic table design, data storage, data ingestion techniques, and workload management. You will also learn about the effect of node and cluster sizing.

Course Title: Exam Readiness: AWS Certified Security - Specialty
Description: We have updated this course on October 7, 2022 to correct a problem that was impacting course completion. If you are enrolled in the course and have not completed it, your progress may be impacted. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause

Course Title: Exam Readiness: AWS Certified DevOps Engineer – Professional
Description: The AWS Certified DevOps Engineer – Professional exam validates technical expertise in provisioning, operating, and managing distributed application systems on the AWS platform. Join this advanced-level course to learn how to prepare for the exam by exploring the exam’s topic areas and how they map to DevOps on AWS and to specific areas to study. We will review sample exam questions in each topic area and teach you how to interpret the concepts being tested so that you can more easily eliminate incorrect responses. This course covers the core principles of the DevOps methodology.

Security should be the first concern for any project – maintaining the confidentiality, integrity and availability of your architecture.  Containers present a unique middle ground between full instance management and pure services.  Bertram Dorn, AWS Security Specialist will help you learn how to achieve segregation, control access, organize namespaces, manage memory, secure communications as well as how to create the corresponding risk assessment.

In this curriculum, we’ll explore Amazon’s fully managed ML platform, Amazon SageMaker. Specifically, we’ll discuss how to train and tune models, how certain algorithms are built in, how you can bring your own algorithm, and how to build for particular use cases like recommender systems or anomaly detection.

Course Title: Exam Readiness: AWS Certified Machine Learning - Specialty
Description: This course prepares you to take the AWS Certified Machine Learning – Specialty exam, which validates your ability to design, implement, deploy, and maintain machine learning (ML) solutions.

Customer data comes in all shapes and forms and from every direction. It’s more critical than ever to connect and process all of that data, so that you can enable more data-driven decisions. In this course, Glenn Gillen will show you how to synthesize all of that disparate data using the power of tools like AWS IoT Analytics, Amazon Cognito, AWS Lambda, and Amazon SageMaker, to name a few. You will learn how to aggregate, process, store, and deliver actionable data in new and powerful ways.
